This study evaluated the analgesic effect, efficacy and safety of aceclofenac controlled release (CR) in patients with chronic knee osteoarthritis (OA). A total of 125 subjects were randomly divided into two groups: one group was administered aceclofenac CR once daily and the other was administered aceclofenac immediate release (IR) twice a day for 4 weeks. The outcome measures included a 100-mm visual analogue scale (VAS), Knee injury and Osteoarthritis Outcome Score (KOOS) and range of motion (ROM). Safety was also evaluated by assessing adverse events, vital signs, physical examination findings, clinical laboratory values and electrocardiographic findings.

The results showed that both groups showed improvements in the VAS, KOOS and ROM after 4 weeks of administration. However, the differences between the two groups were not statistically significant. No significant differences were seen in the evaluation of the adverse events, vital sign, physical examination results, clinical laboratory values and electrocardiography.

In conclusion, aceclofenac CR and aceclofenac IR were found to be equally effective in patients with chronic knee OA and the clinical trial results didn't show any significant difference in safety. The new aceclofenac CR formulation was found to be effective and safe with the practical advantage of once daily administration.&lt;/s&gt;&lt;s&gt;
